  "text": "Norway, for example, at only 1.6% [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Maternal mortality in sub--Saharan Africa was 1.0% in the year 2000 (comparable to 16th and 17th century England) with hemorrhage, hypertension (preeclampsia/eclampsia), and infectious diseases as the major causes. By contrast, maternal mortality in Northern Europe was only 0.02% in the year 2000 [CITATION_3] .",
